Imagine you are walking down the street during a massive rainstorm. You see a giant umbrella. Written across the top of this 
umbrella in huge letters is the word: "Math Problems." The umbrella itself isn't a person; it is just a shelter. If you look 
underneath the umbrella, you will see three specific individuals hiding from the rain:

1. The Apple Divider: A person trying to divide 10 apples among zero people.
2. The Pizza Stuffer: A person trying to shove a massive, family-sized pizza into a tiny Tupperware container.
3. The Broken Abacus: A shy person in the corner trying to physically count out "Infinity" on a wooden abacus.

In C#, ArithmeticException is that giant umbrella. It is a broad, overarching category. You will very rarely see the system throw 
a generic ArithmeticException. Instead, the system throws one of the specific "individuals" standing under the umbrella.

## The Technical Reality

In object-oriented programming, exceptions are classes that use Inheritance. ArithmeticException is a base class provided by the .NET 
framework. Underneath it, there are three specific child exceptions that will actually crash your code: 

- DivideByZeroException: Thrown when you try to divide an integer or decimal by zero.
- OverflowException: Thrown when you try to cram a massive value into a data type that cannot physically hold it (like forcing an int into a byte).
- NotFiniteNumberException (The Shy Sibling): Floating-point math (double or float) doesn't crash when divided by zero; it creates theoretical 
  concepts like Infinity or NaN (Not a Number). This exception is thrown when you try to pass one of these theoretical concepts into a strict system 
  (like a graphics engine) that absolutely requires a real, physical, measurable number to function.

## Let's Look at the Code

try 
{
    // A risky math operation based on user input
    int result = PerformRiskyMathOperation();
}
catch (DivideByZeroException) 
{
    Console.WriteLine("Error: You cannot divide by zero!");
}
catch (OverflowException) 
{
    Console.WriteLine("Error: The number you entered is way too big!");
}

## Let's Look at the Code 2

public void DrawLineOnScreen(double length)
{
    // The length might be 'Infinity' if a previous math calculation went weird.
    // We cannot physically draw a line of infinite length on a monitor!
    
    if (double.IsInfinity(length) || double.IsNaN(length))
    {
        // We manually throw the exception because our drawing system 
        // strictly requires a finite number to work.
        throw new NotFiniteNumberException("The length must be a real, measurable number!", length);
    }

    Console.WriteLine($"Drawing a line of length: {length}");
}
